f\u20e3 Verify the import path  \\n\\nMake sure the module that defines `HolidayAgentException` is correctly imported in `GoogleMap.py`.\\n\\n```python\\n# GoogleMap.py \u2013 top of file\\nfrom HolidayAgent.Exceptions import HolidayAgentException   # adjust the path to your project layout\\n```\\n\\nIf the import is wrong, Python might be pulling in a *different* class with a different signature, which would also cause the same error.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 5\ufe0f\u20e3 Full corrected example (Option\u202fA)\\n\\nBelow is a **self\u2011contained** snippet that shows the exception class, the import, and a safe `fetch_map` function that raises the exception correctly.\\n\\n```python\\n# \u2500\u2500 HolidayAgent/Exceptions.py \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Custom exception for the HolidayAgent suite.\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    def __init__(self, error_code: int, error_detail: str):\\n        self.error_code = error_code\\n        self.error_detail = error_detail\\n        super().__init__(f\\\"[{error_code}] {error_detail}\\\")\\n\\n\\n# \u2500\u2500 HolidayAgent/Tools/GoogleMap.py \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\\nimport requests\\nfrom HolidayAgent.Exceptions import HolidayAgentException   # <-- correct import\\n\\nAPI_KEY = \\\"YOUR_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY\\\"   # <-- replace with real key\\n\\ndef fetch_static_map(lat: float, lng: float) -> bytes:\\n    \\\"\\\"\\\"Return raw PNG bytes of a static map centered on (lat, lng).\\\"\\\"\\\"\\n    url = \\\"https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap\\\"\\n    params = {\\n        \\\"center\\\": f\\\"{lat},{lng}\\\",\\n        \\\"zoom\\\": 12,\\n        \\\"size\\\": \\\"600x400\\\",\\n        \\\"key\\\": API_KEY,\\n    }\\n    try:\\n        resp = requests.get(url, params=params, timeout=10)\\n        resp.raise_for_status()\\n        return resp.content\\n    except requests.RequestException as exc:\\n        # <-- raise with BOTH required arguments\\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\\n            error_code=2001,\\n            error_detail=f\\\"Google Maps request failed: {exc}\\\"\\n        ) from exc\\n```\\n\\n*If you prefer Option\u202fB, just replace the `HolidayAgentException` definition with the optional\u2011argument version shown earlier and keep the raise statement as `raise HolidayAgentException(error_detail=\u2026)`.*\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 6\ufe0f\u20e3 Quick sanity test  \\n\\nCreate a tiny script in the same virtual environment to confirm the exception works:\\n\\n```python\\n# test_exception.py\\nfrom HolidayAgent.Exceptions import HolidayAgentException\\n\\ntry:\\n    raise HolidayAgentException(error_code=123, error_detail=\\\"Test error\\\")\\nexcept HolidayAgentException as e:\\n    print(\\\"Caught:\\\", e)          # Expected output: [123] Test error\\n```\\n\\nRun it:\\n\\n```bash\\npython test_exception.py\\n```\\n\\nYou should see:\\n\\n```\\nCaught: [123] Test error\\n```\\n\\nIf you get that output, the class signature is correct.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 7\ufe0f\u20e3 Re\u2011run your original workflow  \\n\\nNow execute the part of the TravelBot that calls `GoogleMap.py`.  \\nYou should either:\\n\\n* **Get the map data** (if the API call succeeds), **or**\\n* **Receive a clean, custom `HolidayAgentException`** with a helpful message (instead of the cryptic `TypeError`).\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 8\ufe0f\u20e3 Checklist \u2013 make sure you\u2019ve done everything\\n\\n| \u2705 | Action |\\n|---|--------|\\n| **1** | Open the file that defines `HolidayAgentException`. |\\n| **2** | Decide whether you want mandatory arguments (Option\u202fA) or optional/defaults (Option\u202fB). |\\n| **3** | Update the `__init__` signature **or** add missing arguments to every `raise HolidayAgentException(...)`. |\\n| **4** | Verify the import statement in `GoogleMap.py` points to the correct module. |\\n| **5** | Run a tiny test script to confirm the exception can be instantiated. |\\n| **6** | Re\u2011run the full TravelBot flow and confirm the error is gone. |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## 9\ufe0f\u20e3 If the problem persists\u2026\\n\\n1. **Copy\u2011paste the exact `raise` line (line\u202f13) and the current `HolidayAgentException` class definition** into a reply \u2013 I can spot mismatches instantly.  \\n2. **Check for multiple definitions** of `HolidayAgentException` (e.g., one in `exceptions.py` and another stale copy elsewhere). Python may be importing the wrong one.  \\n3. **Make sure you saved the file** after editing and that the interpreter is using the updated code (restart the Python process or your IDE\u2019s run configuration).\\n\\n---\\n\\n### \ud83c\udf89 You\u2019re now ready to get rid of the `missing 1 required positional argument: 'error_detail'` error and let your TravelBot fetch Google Maps data (or raise a meaningful custom exception) without crashing. Happy coding! \ud83d\ude80\ud83d\uddfa\ufe0f\",\"type\":\"TextMessage\"},\"inner_messages\":[]},\"name\":\"Travel_Planner\"}", "sender": "Travel_Planner_1d335231-7f6e-44a1-bb6c-636acea1df9a/1d335231-7f6e-44a1-bb6c-636acea1df9a", "receiver": null, "kind": "MessageKind.PUBLISH", "delivery_stage": "DeliveryStage.DELIVER", "type": "Message"}
