.py`\n\n```python\nclass HolidayAgentException(Exception):\n    """Custom exception for the HolidayAgent suite."""\n    def __init__(self, error_code: int, error_detail: str):\n        self.error_code = error_code\n        self.error_detail = error_detail\n        super().__init__(f"[{error_code}] {error_detail}")\n```\n\n### `HolidayAgent/Tools/GoogleMap.py`\n\n```python\nimport requests\nfrom HolidayAgent.Exceptions import HolidayAgentException   # <-- correct import\n\nAPI_KEY = "YOUR_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY"   # replace with a real key\n\ndef fetch_static_map(lat: float, lng: float) -> bytes:\n    """Return PNG bytes of a static map centered on (lat, lng)."""\n    url = "https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap"\n    params = {\n        "center": f"{lat},{lng}",\n        "zoom": 12,\n        "size": "600x400",\n        "key": API_KEY,\n    }\n    try:\n        resp = requests.get(url, params=params, timeout=10)\n        resp.raise_for_status()\n        return resp.content\n    except requests.RequestException as exc:\n        # <-- raise with BOTH required arguments\n        raise HolidayAgentException(\n            error_code=2001,\n            error_detail=f"Google Maps request failed: {exc}"\n        ) from exc\n```\n\nRunning `fetch_static_map(15.5, 73.8)` will now either return the map image **or** raise a clean, informative `HolidayAgentException` instead of the `TypeError`.\n\n---\n\n## 6\ufe0f\u20e3 Quick sanity\u2011check script  \n\nCreate a tiny script in the same environment to confirm the exception works:\n\n```python\n# test_holiday_exception.py\nfrom HolidayAgent.Exceptions import HolidayAgentException\n\ntry:\n    raise HolidayAgentException(error_code=123, error_detail="Test error")\nexcept HolidayAgentException as e:\n    print("Caught:", e)   # Expected output: [123] Test error\n```\n\nRun:\n\n```bash\npython test_holiday_exception.py\n```\n\nYou should see:\n\n```\nCaught: [123] Test error\n```\n\nIf that prints correctly, the class signature is fixed.\n\n---\n\n## 7\ufe0f\u20e3 Re\u2011run your TravelBot workflow  \n\nNow execute the part of the bot that calls `GoogleMap.py`.  \nYou should either:\n\n* **Receive the map data** (if the Google Maps API call succeeds), **or**\n* **Get a nicely formatted `HolidayAgentException`** (e.g., `[2001] Google Maps request failed: …`) instead of the cryptic `TypeError`.\n\n---\n\n## 8\ufe0f\u20e3 Checklist – make sure you’ve done everything\n\n| \u2705 | Action |\n|---|--------|\n| **1** | Open the file that defines `HolidayAgentException`. |\n| **2** | Choose Option\u202fA (supply both args) **or** Option\u202fB (make args optional). |\n| **3** | Update every `raise HolidayAgentException(...)` to match the chosen signature. |\n| **4** | Verify the import statement in `GoogleMap.py` points to the correct module. |\n| **5** | Run the tiny test script to confirm the exception can be instantiated. |\n| **6** | Re\u2011run the full TravelBot flow and confirm the error is gone. |\n\n---\n\n## 9\ufe0f\u20e3 Still seeing the same error?  \n\n1. **Paste the exact line at `GoogleMap.py:13`** (the `raise` statement) **and the current `HolidayAgentException` class definition** into a reply – I can spot mismatches instantly.  \n2. **Search the whole repository** for `class HolidayAgentException`. If there are multiple definitions, you might be importing the wrong one.  \n3. **Restart the Python interpreter / IDE** after editing the files; sometimes a stale module stays in memory.\n\n---\n\n### \U0001f389 You’re now equipped to eliminate the `missing 1 required positional argument: \'error_detail\'` error and let your TravelBot fetch Google Maps data (or raise a meaningful custom exception) without crashing. Happy coding! \U0001f680\U0001f5fa\ufe0f', type='TextMessage')}
